description: From Middle English unwrought, unwroght, unwrouȝt, equivalent to un- +‎ wrought. Doublet of unworked.

adjectives.description: unwrought (comparative more unwrought, superlative most unwrought)

entries.meaning: In the native state, before being worked on; especially used of bars of bullion and other metal
simple past tense and past participle of unwork
examples: […] Do not say‘I love her for her smile — her look — her wayOf speaking gently, — for a trick of thoughtThat falls in well with mine, and certes broughtA sense of pleasant ease on such a day’ —For these things in themselves, Beloved, mayBe changed, or change for thee, — and love so wrought,May be unwrought so. […]
